               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410705-name-173" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410705-name-173" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410705-name-173" type="surname" value="COLES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410705-name-173" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN COLES</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Experimental-gardens, Chalk-road, Islington, and am the wife of John Coles. On the 6th of June, 1840, the prisoner, whom I had known living with Mrs. Harris, came and asked if I would please to give Mrs. Harris charge for a half-sovereign—I put down six shil<lb></lb>lings, six sixpences, three pence, twelve halfpence, and twelve farthings on the counter—he then said, "I have not got the half-sovereign"—I said, "Are you sure you are quite right?"—he said, "Yes, I am quite right, it is for Mrs. Harris"—I should not have given it to him unless he had said so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410705-name-174" type="witnessName">
